 hook your expensive keyboard up to it and run a serial cable to your Then run a program on the workstation to read the serial port and generate fake X keyboard The two main programs I've found to do this are KT and is a sophisticated program capable of controlling the mouse and even moving among widgets on the It requires a server extension XTEST DEC XTRAP or To find out if your server can do this run 'xdpyinfo' and see if any of these strings appear in the extensions If your server doesn't have this you may want to investigate compiling patchlevel or later or bugging your kt is a simpler program which should work with unextended X Another program called xsendevent also exists but I haven't seen Both and kt are available via anonymous ftp from X terminals Also a number of X terminals NCD Tektronics to name a few use PC compatible If you have an X terminal you may be all Try it out with a normal PC keyboard before you go through the trouble of buying an alternative Also some X terminals add extra buttons you may need to keep your original keyboard around for the once in a blue moon that you have to hit the Setup NeXT NeXT had announced that new NeXT machines will use the Apple Desktop Bus meaning any Mac keyboard will Then they announced they were cancelling their hardware If you want any kind of upgrade for an older NeXT do it now Silicon Graphics Silicon Graphics has announced that their newer machines Indigo and beyond will use standard PC compatible keyboards and I don't believe this also applies to the Power Series It's not possible to upgrade an older SGI to use PC keyboards except by upgrading the entire Contact your SGI sales rep for more IBM RS IBM RS keyboards are actually similar to normal PC Unfortunately you can't just plug one You need two things a cable converter to go from the large PC keyboard connector to the smaller PS style DIN and a new device driver for Believe it or not IBM wrote this device driver recently I used it and it However they don't 